46	//
47	// We use the following terminology to describe the different dimensions.
48	//
49	// B:  Batch size (number of sequences),
50	// L:  Sequence length,
51	// D:  Hidden dimension,
52	// H:  Number of heads,
53	// Dh: Hidden dimension per head - Dh = D / H.
54	//
55	// The different kernels assign a threadblock for B x H pair. The grid has size (1, B, H). We use
56	// 64, 128 and 256 threads per block.
57	//
58	// Each threadblock loads Dh values from Q and its associated bias. The kernels run a loop to
59	// compute Q * K^T where K is loaded from a cache buffer -- except for the current timestep. The
60	// cache buffer helps with memory accesses and contains keys with bias.
61	//
62	// The layout of the cache buffer for the keys is [B, H, Dh/x, L, x] where x == 8 for FP16 and
63	// x == 4 for FP32 where the fastest moving dimension (contiguous data) is the rightmost one. The
64	// values for x are chosen to create chunks of 16 bytes.
65	//
66	// The different kernels use 1, 2 or 4 threads per key (THREADS_PER_KEY). The size of the LDGs
67	// depends on the number of threads per key. Each thread sums Dh / THREADS_PER_KEY elements. At
68	// the end of each iteration of the Q * K^T loop, we perform a reduction between lanes using an
69	// HMMA instruction (Tensor Core). Each Q * K^T valuey is stored in shared memory in FP32.
70	//
71	// After that loop, a parallel softmax is computed across the different Q * K^T values stored in
72	// shared memory.
73	//
74	// The kernel ends with a loop over the values in V. We use THREADS_PER_VALUE to control how many
75	// timesteps are computed by loop iteration. As with the keys, the values are read from a cache
76	// except for the current timestep. The layout of the cache buffer for the values is much simpler
77	// as it is [B, H, L, Dh].
78	//
